Currently (Feb 7) the death toll sits at 638, 137 fatalities away from exceeding the SARS outbreak. Over the past week, an average of 60 fatalities occurred daily (though in the past week this number has been over 70). This is likely an underestimate of the fatality rate since the rate has been increasing daily. If this trend continues, a conservative estimate of 60 fatalities a day would put the Wuhan coronavirus exceeding the SARS outbreak by Feb 10. This is days and days before the first deadline of Feb 15, so even if there was some sort of black swan event, the Wuhan coronavirus would still beat SARS in this given time.

Small increase to the 'before Feb. 15' question option, partly based upon the following updated information:

When will fatalities caused by the Wuhan coronavirus (2019-nCoV) exceed those from Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS), according to the World Health Organization (WHO)? Jan 30 WHO reports 178 fatalities in 7818 cases roughly one month after disease was noticed. At a constant rate, 35K cases would be required to exceed SARS, which is roughly 4-5 times today's known cases. It would appear that the number of cases would be reached by 15 Feb, but assume better care of those infected would reduce fatalities.

One more comment: The question asks about WHO reporting. Currently the WHO is publishing updates daily and I'll assume that will continue. However their reports seem to generally lag the news reports by about a day. I assume they are more conservative in their methodology and perhaps also have an approval process that delays publications. The net result is that I need to add 1-2 days to my estimate.

Based on yesterday's (1/30) data, it appears that relative to my model: 1) Rate of growth of suspected cases was lower than expected (by me) yesterday. Is exponential growth rate slowing?. ~25% yesterday vs ~50%/day for the prior week. This has also translated to slowing in the growth of confirmed cases. ~25% yesterday vs ~45-50% for the prior week. I'm going to assume that the rate of exponential growth will continue to decline sharply. Modeling 25% for a few more days and then 20%. 2) Severity dropping slightly: 11% severe / confirmed (vs 13% prior week). Also death rate (current deaths / current severe cases, which is different than a typical definition of death rate) stable or down a bit a 2.5-3%. I'm assuming 2% going forward.
What a turn around! This virus has spread more aggressively than predicted and has higher percentage of fatality. Too bad that I have to upgrade my analysis in just a day.

The Wuhan coronavirus has reached over 200 deaths in about one month; SARS killed 774 over 9 months. Chinese hospitals are facing severe resource shortages which is significantly increasing the possibility that those who need treatment will not receive it (NYT), additionally the fact that so little is known about the virus at this point leaves the possibility for dangerous mutations beyond the current known rates of transmission (Foreign Policy). Despite the strong response China has taken in quarantining Wuhan, it is likely that the damage has already been done to the residents of Wuhan and an approaching increase in deaths due to lack of treatment and continued transmission in overloaded hospitals is inevitable.

Revising my forecast. The numbers below put my expectation right around Feb 15th. If I do my calculation another way, by simply observing the exponential growth of reported deaths, I get an estimate of around Feb 6th when we exceed 800. If the growth rate starts to show signs of dropping below exponential in the coming days (which seems likely) then I'll need to revise that forecast.

Currently there are roughly 6k confirmed (with lab analysis) cases which presumably represents the majority of the serious cases. There are an additional 9k suspected cases and 60k people in quarantine. The number of confirmed cases has been following a steady exponential growth through yesterday (1/28 in china) and has been roughly doubling every 2 days.

The death rate has grown at a steady 30% per day, and the chances of underreporting are non-negligible. However, coronavirus treatments have improved considerably since SARS, and this disease seems much less lethal than that. It is not unrealistic to expect governments to converge on a strong treatment regimen before too long.

The following report implies about a 2.5% death rate from the disease [1]. This seems pretty reasonable and if that number stays constant there would need to be about 30,000 cases for there to be over 774 deaths. That seems possible, but highly unlikely to occur before February 15th. I think it is also entirely possible that we never reach the 30,000 cases necessary. I think the most likely outcomes are either this takes off pretty soon (and we reach it during late February, March, or it never infects the requisite number of people.

Not as quick or sure to kill as Sars. Higher transmission rate though and an excellent incubation time coupled with a window of infection makes it a good candidate for further mutation into something more unpleasant but that won't be seen (if at all) until later in the year. A little more insidious and slower burning than Sars in that it's believed to be fairly contagious for a good asymptomatic period..... ie you have it but you don't know it. With China a bit slow to get off the mark and handle this I fear we may be looking at exceeding sars figures before summer.... I hope I'm wrong.

Fears over the Wuhan coronavirus are severely overblown IMHO. The fatality rate for it are significantly less than for SARS. The basic reproduction rate (the average number of people infected by one infected person), it looks, is also less.

Unfortunately, right now it is more probable than not that the number of death will go above that one of the SARS in a very short time. Right now we have had an exponential increase in the number of cases (and the number of deaths), which is expected to last at least till about ten days after the quarantine of Wuhan began (leaving at least 4 more days of exponential growth).
Wuhan cases alone doubling every ~38 hours, deaths even faster. Likely to accelerate when deaths begin in other countries.

- The 2003 epidemic of SARS-Cov resulted in more than 8,000 cases, affected 26 countries, and killed 774 people (WHO data). Since 2004, only a small number of cases have occurred as a result of laboratory accidents or, possibly, through animal-to-human transmission (Guangdong, China). https://www.cdc.gov/sars/index.html https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/28/coronavirus-vs-sars-health-experts-on-the-key-differences.html
Roughly, we have 100 fatalities in a time of 4-6 weeks. Projecting that if the total number goes above 774 that will take approximately 5-6 months from beginning of February. i.e. July.

Over 100 as of right now and increase is much faster than linear. Improved reporting as more test kits for 2019-nCoV are produced is likely to be a factor in an even higher rate of increase on reported deaths.
